<DOC><DOCNO> AP890410-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1508EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Earns-DowJones     04-10 0366</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Earns-Dow Jones,0380</SECOND><HEAD>Dow Jones Posts Big Rise in 1st-Qtr Profit with One-Time Gain</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dow Jones andamp; Co. said Monday its profit nearlydoubled from a year ago because of a big one-time gain from thesale of a cable television investment, but weakness in financialadvertising drove its operating income down by 12.5 percent.   Dow Jones said its profit rose to $200 million, or $1.99 ashare, in the first three months of the year from $103.6 million,or $1.08 per share, a year earlier.   First-quarter revenue rose 3.6 percent to $406.8 million from$392.5 million a year earlier.   The latest results included an after-tax gain of $164.1 millionfrom the sale in January of the company's 17 percent stake inContinental Cablevision Inc., a cable system operator. The 1988results included a gain of $64.4 million from the sale of abook-publishing subsidiary, Richard D. Irwin Inc.   Excluding those one-time gains, DowJones said its earnings fell8.4 percent to $35.9 million from $39.2 million a year earlier.   Dow Jones said its operating income, or earnings before taxes,interest and other income, fell 12.5 percent to $79.8 million from$91.1 million.   The decline was blamed mainly on continuing weakness infinancial advertising at the Wall Street Journal, its flagshippublication.   Revenue at the business publications segment fell 4.8 percent to$182.9 million and operating income fell 33.1 percent to $21.8million, the company said.   That segment includes results from the Wall Street Journal,Barron's, the Far Eastern Economic Review and other publications.   Dow Jones said its information services segment had a 14.5percent increase in revenue to $169.1 million while operatingincome rose 0.6 percent to $54.6 million. That includes resultsfrom Telerate Inc., in which Dow Jones owns a 67 percent stake.   Excluding Telerate's results, Dow Jones said the informationservices group consisting of Dow Jones News Service, Dow Jones-NewsRetrieval and other newswire and electronic services, reported a7.6 percent rise in revenue and a 6.1 pecent increase in operatingincome.   Ottaway Newspapers Inc., the community newspapers segment of DowJones, had operating income of $7.4 million, down 13.6 percent, andrevenue of $54.8 million, up 3.9 percent.</TEXT></DOC>